Project Introduction¶

For this project, we will be using the Wine Quality Dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. The dataset contains different charactersitics of several Portugese wines. Quality is the dependent variable. Better quality wines have a score of 10 while the lowest quality wine has a score of 0. The predictors of the wine are:

  • Fixed Acidity
  • Volatile Acidity
  • Citric Acid
  • Residual Sugar
  • Chlorides
  • Free Sulfur Dioxide
  • Total Sulfur Dioxide
  • Density
  • pH
  • Sulphates
  • Alcohol

Originally, we had 2 different datasets consiting of white wine and red wine. I will combine the two and make color_red a predictor.

Using this dataset, we will attempt categorize wines by their quality. We will use several methods such as an unsupervised kmeans, random forest, support vector machines, multinomial logistic regression

Correlation¶

It is important we look at the correlation of the predictors. Highly correlated predictors could mean our predictors are providing redundant information. Some models are highly inaccurate when predictors face this issue. For example, Logistic Regression is a Generalized Linear Model (GLM). Thus, multicollinearity could cause inaccurracies with predictors. This can hurt the interpretability of our model. Sometimes, the collinearity issues cause the model to fail in converging into a unique solution. Also, models such as K-means suffer from the curse of dimensionality. Therefore, reducing the number of predictors could help performance.

As we can see from the plot below, total_sulfur_density is highly correlated with with color_red and free_sulfur_dioxide. Thus, we will drop total_sulfur_density.

Continuous Predictors¶

Most of our predictors are normally distributed. However,volatile acidity and residual sugar are slightly skewed to the right. By themeselves, the distributions are quite concerning. However, for some models, such as random forest, the distribution of predictors isn't as concerning. However, for logistic regression, we need to make sure there are no outliers among the predicors. For models such as K-means, we need to standardize our predictors so that one feature isn't contributing more to the distance measures than others. For example, fixed acidity has a range of 0-16 units. However, volatile acidity has a range from 0-1.6. When calculating distance measures in K-means, fixed acidity will count more towards the distance measure than volatile acidity. At this time, we will not apply transformations to our predictor variables. We'll only apply transformations to meet the assumptions of the model when using.

Continuous Predictors vs Quality¶

Next, we would like to visualize each continuous predictor vs our response variable quality. We would be concerened with a predictors if the distributions per level of quality were the same. If a predictor had the same distribution per level of quality, we will know the predictor doesn't add much value in prediction.

As we can see below, each predictor has different distributions per level of quality. Here are some key points shown by the boxplots:

  • Lower quality wine tends to have higher volatile acidity, density and
  • Higher quality wine tend to have higher citric acid, free sulfur dioxide, and alcohol content

Model Candidates¶

For our dataset, we will attempt to build the following models:

  • Multi-nomial Logistic Regression
    • We want to build this model because it is the mode interpretable. If we can build a model that is highly interpretable, we can understand how different factors contribute to wine quality classification
  • K-means Clustering
    • Using a non parameteric method may work better on our dataset. We have a small amount of predictors so we won't face the curse of dimensionality
    • On the other end, our dataset has an unequal count in the levels of response variable. With using k-means as an unsupervised method, this can cause issues with clustering accurately.
  • Random Forest
    • Random Forest is another nonparametric method. However, it builds a forest of decision trees by selecting a subset of features to buil don each tree.
    • The most chosen level from all the trees will classify the observation

Because our data has small dimensionality with predictors we can transform, k-means seems as it would perform well. After further looking into the response variable distribution, I believe it would be the worse predictor of the three. On the other hand, I believe Random Forest will perform the best as it can catch interactions we may not find in Logistic Regression and the uneven distribution isn't as large as problem as k-means.

Accuracy will be used to compare the three different models as we are more concerned with classifying with the correct class than Type I or Type II error

Logistic Regression¶

First, we need to train a logistic regression model. After fitting, the model has an accuracy of 54.27%

In [93]:
#Compare different permutations to get the correct one
def label_permutation(labels, cluster_labels): 
    """
    labels: labels dataframe object
    cluster_labels: clustering label prediction output
    n : the number of clusters
    Returns permuted label order and accuracy.
    """
    perms = list(itertools.permutations(labels.unique()))
    acc=[]
    for i in range(len(perms)):
        mapdict = dict(zip(list(y_train.unique()),list(perms[i])))
        yt = labels.apply(lambda x: mapdict[x]) 
        acc.append(accuracy_score(yt, cluster_labels))
    idx = np.argmax(acc)
    return perms[idx], acc[idx]

Model Comparison and Analysis
¶

Model Accuracy
Logistic Regression 54.27%
Random Forest 67.44%
K-means 21.19%

  • As expected, K-means performed the worst at 21.19%. K-means fails when there aren't equal observations for each class. In our case, most of our data belonged to the class of 5 and 6. On the other hand, there were barely any observations for a quality of 3, 4, 8 or 9. Thus, the algorithm couldn't accurately convere on a stable mean compared to qualitied of 5 and 6.

  • Multinomial. Logistic Regression performed ok. The lack of interactions and other transformations that could have been applied causes the lack of accuracy. However, the multinomial is more difficult to interpret compared to Binary Logistic Regression or Random Forest. This is even more true after we standardized the predictors.

  • Random Forest Performed the best. The model was able to capture interaction between predictors. Also, because of the use of subsets within different trees, we can interpret the most important factors used with decision making.

Thus, going forward we will use the Random Forest Model

Model Tuning¶

Random Forest Models are known for over fitting. We need to evaluate our model using different hyperparameters and predictors subsets. Not only will this help with generalization, it will also improve our model speed.

We can use GridSearchCV to find the best combination of hyperparameters.

Some parameters we will fine tune are:

  • criterion: what to use as measurement within the tree
  • Max Depth: The maximum number of levels for each decision tree
  • Max features: the number of features to consider for each decision tree within the forest
  • Min_samples_split: the minimum number of observations required to split a branch
  • n_estimators: the number of trees to use in the forest.

After GridSearch we can see our model improved by about 1.2%.

Final Model Evaluation¶

Overall, our model does not classify wine quality very well. We predicted this issue when reviewing our model response distribution. When wine quality is 5, 6, or 7, our model classifies fairly accurately. However, do to the lack of data, our model doesn' classify qualities of 3,4 5, 8, or 9 well.

  • Qualities of 4 and 8 have fairly high precision. In other words, when our model predicts a model is 4, there's a high probability it will be 4. The same can be said for 8. On the other hand, their recall is very low. Thus, our model does correctly classify 4 or 8 at a high rate.
    • With more data, the recall would increase and the precision would decrease. In our case, we would like both metrics to be balanced
  • Overall, our model has a 70% accuracy on the test set. This is higher than our validation set. Thus, our model generalizes very well.
  • Each of the predictors has an importance above 0.05. Thus, they are all relevant to the quality of the wine.
    • However, the amount of alcohol is the most contributing factor to the quality of the wine
    • Volatile acidity is the next most important
    • Fixed Acidity and citric acid contriubte the least to the quality of the wine

Conclusion and Recommendation for Future Project¶

  • Overall, our model performs well for wine qualities of 5,6,7. However, due to lack of data, it fails to classify quality of 3,4,8 or 9 correctly. We didn't have any values of wine quality of 1, 2 or 10. Thus, that is another issue with the dataset we had
  • When discussing quality wine, alcohol content is the most important factor followed by volatile acidity
  • The least important predictors are fixed acidity and citric acid
  • For future projects
    • more wine would need to be collected to accurately represent the different qualities in the distribution.
    • With more wines, other models such as Logistic Regression may converge to a better model
    • May need to deparate quality into a binary category. Higher than 5 is a good wine while 5 or lower it bad. This may result in classifying if a wine is strictly good or not
